[Student "E"]
{[showcards N:D5]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown.

Partner led the \SJ, won by dummy's \SQ. The \D5 is now played from dummy. What do you play?

Play the \D2. Considering that North opened 1NT, he must have the \DQ for this play to make sense. 

So if you put on your \DA, North will have TWO \D winners established. If instead you play low, then North cannot get a second \D trick and will have to look elsewhere for his ninth trick. As you can see, he is not going to be able to find it.}
[Play "W"]SJ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:KQJ82.A8762.8.A2 T4.JT54.963.JT93 A6.K93.AQJ74.KQ7 9753.Q.KT52.8654"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 3D pass 3H pass 3NT pass 4H pass 4NT pass 5H pass 6H all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "c3d4d230afc9b65e7aeb6829de2968537566dbf5eb1af45ab45062616e89dbbf"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/second_hand_play"]
[Student "W"]
{[showcards S:H2]

You are South. The bidding has been as shown.

Your lead of the \CJ was won by East with the \CA. East then played the \H2 and you must decide whether to split your honors.

Play the \H4, do not split your Honors.

East's bidding showed at least 5 \Hs, so assuming he holds both the \H A Q, it would be silly for him to finesse the \H9 on the first trump play.

As it turns out, when you play low East calls for dummy's \HK, North's \HQ falls and you now have 2 trump tricks. If you had played the \H10 you would have tossed away the setting trick.}
[Play "W"]CJ

